{"title_page": "Wave Financial", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Wave Financial Inc.\n| logo = Wave logo RGB.png\n| logo_size = \n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| foundation = [[Canada]] (2009)\n| location_city = [[Toronto]]\n| location_country = [[Canada]]\n| key_people = Kirk Simpson (co-founder and CEO),<br /> James Lochrie (co-founder)<Br /> Les Whiting (Chief Financial Services Officer)\n| industry = [[Small business software]]\n| owner = [[H&R Block]]\n| num_employees = 205 (January 2019)\n| homepage = [http://www.waveapps.com/ www.waveapps.com]\n}}\n\n'''Wave''' is a company that provides financial services and software for small businesses. Wave is headquartered in the [[Leslieville]] neighbourhood in [[Toronto|Toronto, Canada]].\n\nThe company's first product was a free online [[accounting software]] designed for businesses with 1-9 employees, followed by [[Invoice|invoicing]], personal finance and receipt-scanning software (OCR).<ref>{{cite web|title=Wave's newest features|url=https://zipbooks.com/free-wave-accounting-alternative/|website=ZipBooks.com|publisher=ZipBooks|accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref> In 2012, Wave began branching into financial services, initially with Payments by Wave (credit card processing) and Payroll by Wave, followed by Lending by Wave<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ondeck.com/company/in-the-news/press-releases/ondeck-partners-with-wave-to-launch-lending-by-wave-small-business-financing-powered-by-ondeck/|website=OnDeck|title=OnDeck Partners with Wave to Launch \"Lending by Wave\" Small Business Financing Powered by OnDeck|accessdate=7 April 2017}}</ref> in February 2017.\n\n==Features and integrations==\nThe company's initial product, Accounting by Wave, is a [[Double-entry bookkeeping system|double entry accounting]] tool. Services include direct bank data imports, invoicing and expense tracking, customizable chart of accounts, and journal transactions. Accounting by Wave integrates with expense tracking software Shoeboxed, and [[e-commerce]] website [[Etsy]].\n\nThe next product launched was Payroll by Wave, which was launched in 2012 after the acquisition of SmallPayroll.ca.<ref>{{cite web|author=Canada |url=http://www.techvibes.com/blog/wave-accounting-acquires-small-payroll-and-relaunches-as-wave-payroll-2011-11-02 |title=Wave Accounting acquires Small Payroll and relaunches as Wave Payroll |publisher=Techvibes.com |date=2011-11-02 |accessdate=2012-10-31}}</ref> Payroll by Wave is only available in U.S.A. and Canada.\n\nInvoicing by Wave is an offshoot of the company's earlier accounting tools.\n\nAdditional products launched on or shortly after the company's rebrand<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/12/17/with-500k-users-wave-rebrands-to-tell-the-world-it-isnt-just-about-free-accounting-anymore/ |title=With 500K Users, Wave Rebrands To Tell The World It Isn't Just About Free Accounting Anymore |publisher=[[TechCrunch]] |date=December 17, 2012 |accessdate=April 23, 2013}}</ref> in December 2012 include:  \n* a credit card processing tool, Payments by Wave, built initially on an integration with [[Stripe (company)|Stripe]] credit card processing. However Wave does not report merchant fees correctly for countries where Stripe charges a tax such as GST. In these cases the merchant fees are reported without tax and do not match your Stripe account. \n* a receipt scanning tool, Receipts by Wave<ref>{{cite web|last=Etherington|first=Darrell|title=Wave Debuts Free Receipt Scanning And Management Tool To Add To Its Free Accounting Platform|url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/04/10/wave-accounting-free-receipt-scanning/|accessdate=10 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Wave signed an agreement to provide its platform on RBC's online business banking site. The RBC-Wave service will be co-branded.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bankinnovation.net/2017/09/digital-accounting-service-wave-signs-collaboration-deal-with-royal-bank-of-canada/|title=Digital Accounting Service Wave Signs Deal with Royal Bank of Canada|date=2017-09-14|work=Bank Innovation|access-date=2017-12-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Taxes supported ==\nWave currently supports adding custom taxes via settings. However you must manually apply the tax for every transaction as they come in, there is no way to automate it.\n\nIt currently only supports tax exclusive pricing, such as US Sales tax, where taxes are added on top of prices quoted. This has two effects:\n\n* When scanning receipts you must manually add the tax, and input the tax amount.\n* When making an invoice, you must put in a price before tax, and it will add the tax on top.\n\nThis makes it unable to handle taxes countries like Australia where prices must be quoted inclusive of all taxes such as GST. There is no way to set an invoice total and have Wave calculate the tax portion by %. While this is fine for B2B businesses, this makes the software unsuitable for any B2C businesses.\n\n==Pricing and business model==\nWave provides its software for free.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.waveapps.com/pricing/|title=Wave Accounting Pricing|website=Wave|publisher=Wave|accessdate=7 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nRevenue from the company comes from the paid financial services the company offers:\n* Payments by Wave: Card Processing which includes Debit, Credit and Prepaid Cards as well as ACH (Bank Payments) - Fees are a percentage of the transaction.\n* Payroll by Wave: Monthly subscription fee plus usage fees\n\nWave previously included advertising on its pages as a source of revenue. Advertising was removed in January 2017.\n\nWave's software is free, as opposed to [[freemium]], in that the tools can be used without tiers or limits indefinitely.\n\nWave does not currently disclose its revenue or financial statements publicly. However, media reports in 2016<ref>{{cite web|last1=Galang|first1=Jessica|title=WAVE RAISES $14.6 MILLION WITH GOAL TO GROW TEAM TO 150 AND CONTINUE MOBILE DEVELOPMENT|url=http://betakit.com/wave-raises-14-6-million-with-goal-to-grow-team-to-150-and-continue-mobile-development/|website=betakit|publisher=BetaKit|accessdate=7 April 2017}}</ref> indicated annual revenues of $20 million at that time. In 2017 Wave raised $24m (USD) in funding led by NAB Ventures.<ref>{{cite web|title=Canadian fintech firm Wave raises $24M in Series D funding led by NAB Ventures|url=http://www.econotimes.com/Canadian-fintech-firm-Wave-raises-24M-in-Series-D-funding-led-by-NAB-Ventures-733774|website=econotimes|accessdate=2 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nCEO Kirk Simpson and CPO James Lochrie launched Wave Accounting Inc. in July 2009. Wave Accounting launched to the public on November 16, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|author=Canada |url=http://www.techvibes.com/blog/wave-accounting-launches-free-service-for-small-businesses |title=Wave Accounting launches free service for small businesses |publisher=Techvibes.com |date=2010-11-20 |accessdate=2012-10-31}}</ref>  In June 2011 Series A funding led by OMERS Ventures<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.omersventures.com/ |title=Home |publisher=OMERS Ventures |date= |accessdate=2012-10-31}}</ref> was closed. In September 2011, FedDev Ontario invested one million dollars in funding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/2011/09/13/toronto-startups-get-1m-in-federal-funding/ |title=Toronto startups get $1M in federal funding &#124; Growth Strategies &#124; Resource Centre &#124; Entrepreneur &#124; Financial Post |publisher=Business.financialpost.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-31}}</ref> In October 2011, a $5-million investment led by U.S. venture capital firm [[Charles River Ventures]] was announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/2011/10/14/toronto-startup-raises-5m-in-latest-wave-of-funding/ |title=Toronto startup raises $5M in latest 'Wave' of funding &#124; FP Tech Desk &#124; Financial Post |publisher=Business.financialpost.com |date=2011-10-14 |accessdate=2012-10-31}}</ref> In May 2012, Wave Accounting closed its series B financing round led by [[The Social+Capital Partnership]], with follow-on participation from [[Charles River Ventures]] and OMERS Ventures.<ref>{{cite web|author=Wednesday, May 16, 2012 |url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/05/16/wave-accounting-12m-series-b/ |title=Wave Accounting Raises $12M from Social+Capital Partnership, Charles River Ventures & OMERS Ventures |publisher=TechCrunch |date=2012-05-16 |accessdate=2012-10-31}}</ref>\n \nWave acquired a company called Small Payroll in November 2011,<ref>{{cite web|author=Canada |url=http://www.techvibes.com/blog/wave-accounting-acquires-small-payroll-and-relaunches-as-wave-payroll-2011-11-02 |title=Wave Accounting acquires Small Payroll and relaunches as Wave Payroll |publisher=Techvibes.com |date=2011-11-02 |accessdate=2012-10-31}}</ref> which was later launched as a payroll product called Wave Payroll. In February 2012, Wave officially launched Wave Payroll to the public in Canada,<ref>{{cite web|author=Canada |url=http://www.techvibes.com/blog/wave-accounting-launches-wave-payroll-in-canada-2012-02-01 |title=Wave Accounting launches Wave Payroll in Canada |publisher=Techvibes.com |date=2012-02-01 |accessdate=2012-10-31}}</ref> followed by the American release in November of the same year.\n\nIn August, 2012, the company announced the acquisition of Vuru.co,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waveaccounting.com/blog/wave-buys-vuru/ |title=Vuru.co is now part of the Wave family - Wave Accounting - Free Small Business Accounting Software |publisher=Wave Accounting |date=2012-08-21 |accessdate=2012-10-31}}</ref> an online stock-tracking service. Terms of the deal were not disclosed.\n\nIn December 2012 the company rebranded itself as Wave to emphasize its broadened spectrum of services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/12/17/with-500k-users-wave-rebrands-to-tell-the-world-it-isnt-just-about-free-accounting-anymore/ |title=With 500K Users, Wave Rebrands To Tell The World It Isn't Just About Free Accounting Anymore |publisher=[[TechCrunch]] |date=December 17, 2012 |accessdate=April 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, 2019 the company acquired Every, a Toronto-based fintech company that provides business accounts and debit cards to small businesses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://betakit.com/wave-acquires-every-to-expand-financial-services-integration/|title=Wave acquires Every to expand financial services integration|date=2019-03-04|website=BetaKit|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref>\n\nOn June 11, 2019, the company announced it was being acquired by tax preparation company, [[H&R Block]], for $537 million<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.waveapps.com/wave-to-be-acquired-by-hr-block-for-537-million/|title=Wave gets acquired by H&R Block|date=2019-06-11|website=Bravely Go|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>.\n==See also==\n* [[Accounting software]]\n* [[Comparison of accounting software]]\n*[[List of free and open-source software packages|List of free and open source software packages]]\n* [[Web application]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Accounting software}}\n\n[[Category:Accounting software]]\n[[Category:Cloud applications]]\n[[Category:Proprietary software]]\n[[Category:Software companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Web applications]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Wave Financial Inc.\n| logo = Wave logo RGB.png\n| logo_size = \n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| foundation = [[Canada]] (2009)\n| location_city = [[Toronto]]\n| location_country = [[Canada]]\n| key_people = Kirk Simpson (co-founder and CEO),<br /> James Lochrie (co-founder)<Br /> Les Whiting (Chief Financial Services Officer)\n| industry = [[Small business software]]\n| owner = [[H&R Block]]\n| num_employees = 205 (January 2019)\n| homepage = [http://www.waveapps.com/ www.waveapps.com]\n}}\n\n'''Wave''' is a company that provides financial services and software for small businesses. Wave is headquartered in the [[Leslieville]] neighbourhood in [[Toronto|Toront